  <!-- 30-Second Take-Away -->
  <h2 id="takeaway">30-Second Take-Away</h2>

  <p>The main differences between a decanter and disc-stack centrifuge are:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>A decanter centrifuge's axis of rotation is horizontal, whereas a disc-stack centrifuge bowl rotates around a vertical axis.</li>
    <li>Decanter centrifuges typically exert around <strong>3,000 Gs</strong> compared to <strong>8,000+ Gs</strong> generated by a disc-stack centrifuge.</li>
    <li>Sludge handling capacity is much higher for a decanter centrifuge compared to a disc-stack centrifuge. A decanter centrifuge can handle up to <strong>50% sludge</strong>, while a disc-stack centrifuge is limited to <strong>8% sludge</strong> by volume.</li>
    <li>With a higher G-force, a disc-stack centrifuge can separate particles down to a <strong>0.5-micron level</strong>. A decanter centrifuge typically separates particles, which are <strong>100 microns or larger</strong>.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>This article compares the different technical aspects of decanter centrifuges and disc centrifuges. We will compare all the factors important to the end-user. These will include physical, operational, performance, and maintenance factors between these centrifuge types.</p>


  <!-- Overview Section -->
  <h2 id="overview">Overview of Decanter and Disc Centrifuge Operation</h2>

  <h3>Decanter Centrifuge</h3>

  <img
    src="/images/difference-between-decanter-centrifuge-disc-centrifuge/decanter-bowl-scroll-rotation-400.webp"
    alt="Conveyor Rotation inside Decanter Bowl"
    width="400" height="163"
    loading="lazy"
    class="img-cap-400"
  />
  <p class="text-xs text-text-muted mt-2 text-center"><strong>Decanter Bowl Cross Section</strong></p>

  <p>A <a href="/decanter-centrifuge/">decanter centrifuge</a> is an industrial machine designed to separate solids from liquids continuously. This process is also known as de-watering or sludge thickening.</p>

  <p>Accelerated sedimentation is the key to the operation of all centrifuges. A decanter centrifuge <strong>exerts a force up to 4,000 times that of gravity</strong> to affect this settling. High-speed rotation is the cause of this force multiplier effect. This <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_centrifugation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">differential centrifugation</a> is a widely used physical phenomenon.</p>

  <p>As shown in the image above, the rapid rotation of the bowl causes a high centrifugal force in a radially outward direction, i.e., away from the rotating axis of the bowl. This force causes the denser solid particles to move towards the bowl wall (outward) while displacing the liquid inward.</p>

  <p>The auger (also known as screw, scroll, or conveyor) rotates within the bowl at a speed different than that of the bowl. A planetary gearbox attached to the decanter bowl rotates the auger.</p>

  <p>The auger scrapes or pushes the collected solids towards the tapered end of the decanter. Here the solids are pushed up the 'beach' and exit the bowl through the solids' discharge ports.</p>

  <p>The path of the solids along the 'beach' is against the centrifugal force, which is directed radially outwards. This force causes the liquid to separate from the solids causing dry solids to exit the bowl.</p>

  <p>The separated liquid(s) create a 'pond' inside the accumulated solids layer around the bowl periphery. Liquid discharge ports located at the far end of the bowl allow the separated liquids to exit the bowl.</p>

  <p>A detailed writeup on decanter centrifuges is on our blog <a href="/decanter-centrifuge/">Decanter Centrifuge details, including uses, benefits, capacities, price-range, etc.</a></p>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
